<h3>Halogenoalkanes</h3>

<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Halogenoalkanes (or alkyl halides) are organic compounds containing one or more halogen atoms (F, Cl, Br, I) attached to an alkyl chain. They are important intermediates in organic synthesis.
</p>

<h2 style="color: lightseagreen; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">General Formula</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    The general formula for halogenoalkanes is <b>R-X</b>, where R is an alkyl group and X is a halogen atom.
</p>

<h2 style="color: lightseagreen; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Classification of Halogenoalkanes</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Primary (1°):</b> The carbon bonded to the halogen is attached to one other alkyl group. Example: CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>Cl (ethyl chloride).</li>
    <li><b>Secondary (2°):</b> The carbon bonded to the halogen is attached to two alkyl groups. Example: CH<sub>3</sub>CHClCH<sub>3</sub> (2-chloropropane).</li>
    <li><b>Tertiary (3°):</b> The carbon bonded to the halogen is attached to three alkyl groups. Example: (CH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>3</sub>CCl (tert-butyl chloride).</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: lightseagreen; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Physical Properties</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Boiling Points:</b> Higher than alkanes of similar molecular mass due to the presence of polar C-X bonds. Increases with the size and number of halogen atoms.</li>
    <li><b>Solubility:</b> Halogenoalkanes are insoluble in water but soluble in organic solvents because they cannot form hydrogen bonds.</li>
    <li><b>Density:</b> Halogenoalkanes are denser than water, particularly those containing heavier halogens like bromine or iodine.</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: lightseagreen; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Reactivity of Halogenoalkanes</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Halogenoalkanes undergo substitution and elimination reactions due to the polar carbon-halogen bond, where the halogen is more electronegative than carbon.
</p>

<h3 style="color: lightseagreen; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Nucleophilic Substitution</h3>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Hydroxide Ions:</b> Halogenoalkanes react with hydroxide ions to form alcohols. Example:
        <code>R-X + OH<sup>-</sup> → R-OH + X<sup>-</sup></code>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Cyanide Ions:</b> Reaction with cyanide ions produces nitriles. Example:
        <code>R-X + CN<sup>-</sup> → R-CN + X<sup>-</sup></code>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Ammonia:</b> Reaction with ammonia forms amines. Example:
        <code>R-X + NH<sub>3</sub> → R-NH<sub>2</sub> + HX</code>.
    </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="color: lightseagreen; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Elimination</h3>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Halogenoalkanes undergo elimination reactions in the presence of a strong base to form alkenes. Example:
    <code>CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>Cl + OH<sup>-</sup> → CH<sub>2</sub>=CH<sub>2</sub> + Cl<sup>-</sup> + H<sub>2</sub>O</code>.
</p>

<h2 style="color: lightseagreen; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Uses of Halogenoalkanes</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Solvents:</b> Used as solvents in industries (e.g., dichloromethane).</li>
    <li><b>Refrigerants:</b> Halogenoalkanes such as chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) were widely used as refrigerants, although their use is now restricted due to environmental concerns.</li>
    <li><b>Synthetic Intermediates:</b> Serve as key intermediates in the synthesis of pharmaceuticals, agrochemicals, and polymers.</li>
</ul>

